g.text: Rhetoric: Absolute rubbish. Your politico-olfactory cortex doesn't deceive you. The smell is coming... from that balcony over there!
You: "I'm working on developing my political consciousness."
You: I can *kind of* smell dreams being ground down by capital.
Jump to: [Rhetoric: "Without a doubt. Your politico-olfa..."]
Kim Kitsuragi: "Well, I'll be over here when you've finished." The lieutenant nudges a piece of trash with his foot.
You: You mean from that scary-looking girl in the old lady coat?
Perception (Smell): The first thing that strikes you is the overwhelming brine. You imagine yourself underwater, a hundred-legged arthropod scuttling along the murky silt at the bottom of the sea...
Rhetoric: Without a doubt. Your politico-olfactory cortex doesn't deceive you. The smell is coming... from that balcony over there!
Kim Kitsuragi: "There's a lot to take in, isn't there?" The lieutenant wrinkles his nose.
Jump to: [Rhetoric: "Without a doubt. Your politico-olfa..."]
Kim Kitsuragi: "You know what? I'll just leave you to it. Carry on, detective."
Rhetoric: The lieutenant lacks your highly developed politico-olfactory cortex. The smell is undeniable. And it's coming... from that balcony up there!
Rhetoric: There it is again! There's a spectral scent haunting this pier, no doubt. And it smells like...
Rhetoric: There! Do you smell that?
Kim Kitsuragi: "I'm struggling to see the connection with our investigation, but I'm sure *all will be revealed* in time."
Kim Kitsuragi: "Still smelling for communists, detective?"
Perception (Smell): It smells like a pier, in other words. A completely ordinary pier, that provokes no ideological associations whatsoever.
You: (Close your eyes and take a deep breath.)
You: Are you saying there's a communist nearby?
Perception (Smell): But then the unmistakable reek of *seagull shit* hits you, buoyed along on the air currents, an acrid melody atop mouldering chords of wood rot and heavy fuel oil.
Kim Kitsuragi: "Everything in order, detective?" The lieutenant gives you a quizzical look.
You: "It's kind of a personal errand."
Esprit de Corps: He'll tolerate this *personal errand*, but his patience is wearing thin.
Rhetoric: Years of turmoil, of hopes and dreams ground beneath the inexorable tides of capital.
Rhetoric: Can you not detect that inimitable whiff of dissatisfaction and restlessness, that sense that the world is in need of dramatic, even violent re-ordering?
Inland Empire: A chance to establish contact with the future! What a beautiful, *terrible* thought...
Kim Kitsuragi: "You do remember that we're investigating a *murder*, yes? I would appreciate it if you reserved your political projects for after-hours."
Savoir Faire: The lieutenant's right. It's sort of amazing how *un-subtly* you're sniffing the air around you, almost like you're *trying* to call attention to yourself.

Rhetoric: What the lieutenant thinks is irrelevant. Your politico-olfactory cortex is lighting up like a holiday display. The scent of communism is overwhelming, and it's coming right... from that balcony over there!
Esprit de Corps: His impatience is feigned. He's actually curious to see how this *personal errand* shakes out.
Perception (Smell): Sea brine, mostly. Because it's a pier.
Drama: The lieutenant issss *not* persuaded, sssssire.
Perception (Smell): Nothing. Or at least, nothing in particular. As far as you're concerned, your nose seems to be purely decorative.
Kim Kitsuragi: "No offence, detective, but you're not particularly *subtle*."
You: (Close your eyes and take a deep breath.)
You: "Just taking in the fresh air, like a normal detective."
"Just taking in the morning air, like a normal detective."
"Just taking in the afternoon air, like a normal detective."
"Just taking in the evening air, like a normal detective."
"Just taking in the night air, like a normal detective."
Rhetoric: Certainement! A precocious communist youth, a symbol of a kinder, more hopeful future. Now's your chance to *establish contact* with your revolutionary brothers and sisters.
